From: Glen Chen <Glen.Chen@calix.com>
Sent: Thursday, April 30, 2026 11:40 AM
To: Sanjay Agrawal <Sanjay.Agrawal@calix.com>; Ganga Bhavani <Ganga.Bhavani@calix.com>; Hao Wu <Hao.Wu@calix.com>; Brian Wing <Brian.Wing@calix.com>
Subject: SD VM memory usage
 
Hi All,
I’ve been hearing numerous complaints about how SD VM is running out of resources, and I have also experienced some of them first hand.
The reason for this should not be surprising to anyone:
We are working concurrently on more dev projects
·         AXOS, EXOS, MXOS
·         Increased frequence of builds of multiple depot/workspaces – this has always been a problem, especially with parallel builds – one build can take up 10+GB of memory.
·         Multiple builds – more memory use if concurrently
 
Increased usage of sandbox simulation
·         sandbox simulation enables significant productivity – however, each sandbox instances often require many GB of memory allocation (~4-6GB)
·         Paired up with sandbox often involves local traffic generators, test tools, and topology of multiple sandbox instances.
 
We’ve steadily moved more workflows into the SD VM that requires a web browser:
·         Moving stash into SD brought many workflows into SD (e.g. PR review, JIRA, confluence, …)
·         Browsers (with multiple tabs) often require more memory usage
 
Increased usage of IDE/AI based workflows
·          More people now have VSCode open, which increases memory usage
 
There has NOT been a consistent standard for a SD VM memory allocation:
·         Most developers get ~16GB RAM, and a small amount of swap (~16GB) in SD VM
·         Some with much more RAM (23+GB) – they usually come from one-off requests and handled inconsistently.
·         The rule-rule-thumb of “swap=2xRAM” is not being followed.
 
When peak allocation fails (due to above mem demand increased)
·         linux oom-kill will cause random failure in SD VM ßThis is the key pain point in DEV today
 
To resolve these problems I have the following recommendations:
Make sure total memory (RAM + swap) is a minimum of 48GB (i.e. 16G RAM +32G swap)  ß this must be done for SD VMs for all MXOS developers right away
·         Rollout these changes preemptively instead of waiting for developers to ‘hit the wall’
·         This will hopefully alleviate some short-term pain, with long term solution below.
Review SD VM allocation template and policies for different DEV teams/projects
·         Profile and understand memory usage impact due to Stash and AI workflows -- account for increase memory (not RAM) usage due to stash/vscode/sim, etc
·         Publish and deploy SD VM memory (RAM+Swap) size required for AXOS/EXOS/MXOS based on new profile
Review disk allocation for the SD VM
·         This is required to balance the swap space usage.
·         Currently most SD VM have 80G root filesystem – a tight fit when swap increases.
 
I look forward to your thoughts on how to proceed.
 
Thanks,
-Glen
